{"key":"processedPost-12944444","value":{"id":12944444,"first":12944293,"last":12945319,"when":1279978908,"utime":"07/24/10 04:41 PM","content":"I wouldn't flatten it out too much because drying becomes a concern.&nbsp; Not all sclerotia producing species only form stones at the edges.&nbsp; Some produce stones all the way through.&nbsp; It should be done in six to eight weeks if you use weak liquid coffee to hydrate the rye berries.&nbsp; Leaving the bags longer than that can often lead to the sclerotia going rancid.<br /><br />I show a method of preparing filter patch bags in the <a href=\"http://www.mushroomvideos.com/Sawdust-Woodchips\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer noopener\">sawdust/woodchips</a> chapter of the video where you slip a tyvek sleeve into the bag before sterilizing.&nbsp; This allows steam to vent, but prevents contaminants entering the bag as it cools.&nbsp; This is the method we use on our mushroom farm, and often leave the bags unsealed this way for over a week before inoculation without problems.&nbsp; After inoculation, you can seal the bag with electrical twist ties, or steel tie wire, etc.<br />RR","title":"Re: rye bag sclerotia question. (first post)","forum":"Mushroom Cultivation"}}